05781nam a22007935i 9781845458300DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20102010nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97818454583007 a10.1515/97818454583002doi  a(DE-B1597)636602  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aGN296 .T33 2011 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a306.46100aTechnologized Images, Technologized Bodies /ced. by Jeanette Edwards, Penelope Harvey, Peter Wade. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (270 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tPreface and Acknowledgements -- tCHAPTER 1 Technologized Images, Technologized Bodies -- tCHAPTER 2 Pharmaceutical Witnessing: Drugs for Life in an Era of Direct-toconsumer Advertising -- tCHAPTER 3 Picturing the Brain Inside, Revealing the Illness Outside: A Comparison of the Different Meanings Attributed to Brain Scans by Scientists and Patients -- tCHAPTER 4 Embodied Brains: Why Science Studies Needs the Anthropology of Museums -- tCHAPTER 5 Spectacles of Reason: An Ethnography of Indian Gastroenterologists -- tCHAPTER 6 Technokids? Insulin Pumps Incorporated in Young People’s Bodies and Lives -- tCHAPTER 7 Wearable Augmentations: Imaginaries of the Informed Body -- tCHAPTER 8 ‘Embryos Are Our Baby’: Abridging Hope, Body and Nation in Transnational Ova Donation -- tCHAPTER 9 Living Differently in Time: Plasticity, Temporality and Cellular Biotechnologies -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe modern world is saturated with images. Scientific knowledge of the human body (in all its variety) is highly dependent on the technological generation of visual data – brain and body scans, x-rays, diagrams, graphs and charts. New technologies afford scientists and medical experts new possibilities for probing and revealing previously invisible and inaccessible areas of the body. The existing literature has been successful in mapping the impact and implications of new medical technologies and in marrying the visual and the body but thus far has focused only narrowly on particular kinds of technology or taken only a purely textual/visual (cultural studies) approach to images of the body. Combining approaches from three of the most dynamic and popular fields of contemporary social anthropology – the study of the visual, the study of the technological and the study of the human body – this volume draws these together and interrogates their intersection using insights from ethnographic approaches. Offering a fascinating and wide range of perspectives, the chapters in this volume bring an innovative focus that reflects the authors’ shared interest in ‘the body’ and visualising technologies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aCohn, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDumit, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEcks, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Jeanette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Jeanette, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarvey, Penelope, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarvey, Penny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLandecker, Hannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLorimer, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNahman, Michal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1